The 
Sarcophagidae
(
Diptera
) or flesh flies is a cosmopolitan family of oestroid calyptrates (

) comprising more than 3100 described species currently assigned to about 175 genera, which are classified in three subfamilies: Miltogramminae, Paramacronychiinae and Sarcophaginae (

; 

). The family is biologically diverse and has its peak diversity in warm tropical areas (

, 

). The family is well defined through the possession of a bilobed incubatory pouch from the common oviduct, but the lack of conspicuous synapomorphies in adult external morphology makes 
Sarcophagidae
difficult to key out, and they are often identified from the individual subfamilies (

), or through a complex combination of character states (

). For most species, only males can be reliably identified to species based on morphology (e.g., 

; 

; 

; 

) and often only after examination of the terminalia. Identification based on molecular data is still mainly feasible for species of forensic importance (

; 

; 

; 

) although molecular ‘barcode’ libraries are rapidly accumulating (e.g., 

; 

; 

; 

). Other methods of identification are showing some promise, like cuticular hydrocarbons (

, 

) and wing venation patterns (

; 

), but these are still under development.

All sarcophagids are ovoviviparous, depositing newly-hatched first instar larvae, or more rarely incubated eggs with mature first instar larvae ready to hatch (

). The larvae of most 
Miltogramminae
are kleptoparasites in the nests of aculeate wasps (
Hymenoptera
: Aculeata), but several are necrophagous or sarcosaprophagous feeding on buried carrion (

). The immature sarcophaginae are frequently involved in forensic investigations as entomological evidence found mostly during the first and second instar or throughout the decomposition of ephemeral corpses and carcasses (

; 

; 

; 

; 

). The adult sarcophagids are usually attracted to odours of decay or to nectar (

; 

). Some species of both 
Paramacronychiinae
and 
Sarcophaginae
are obligatory parasites or predators of invertebrates, and others breed as scavengers in dead or dying animals. Some 
Sarcophaginae
have been reared from dung, but in such cases it is possible that the larval food was not the substrate but the insects it contained (

).

Photographs of 

Hoplacephala transfuga
(Villeneuve)

were taken using a BK plus Imaging System from Visionary Digital™ (Palmyra, PA, 
USA
) equipped with a Canon 7D digital camera (in 
NHMDK
). Stacks of images from multiple focal planes were combined using Zerene Stacker (Zerene Systems LLC).All other photographs were taken using a Canon EOS 8OD DSLR camera attached to a Leica Z6 Macroscope with trinocular head (in 
NMWC
). Images were stacked using HeliconFocus v6.22. (HeliconSoft Ltd) extended depth of field software. Calibrated scale bars were added using Adobe Photoshop v.21. Figures for the new species were drawn using a Wild binocular microscope with a camera lucida.

